  "success": true,
  "output": "This is a pure Python/asyncio/SQLite job-scraping pipeline (fetchers → filters → dedup store → notify) — there's no React or any frontend here, so that bucket doesn't apply. I found three real issues worth fixing, in priority order.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `Store.diff()` (`store.py:55-74`)\n\nFor every job in the batch, it does a separate `SELECT` round-trip, then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`. With sources like Amazon/Microsoft/Google configured for `max_pages: 40` (thousands of listings), a single run can issue several thousand sequential SQLite round-trips instead of one.\n\n```python\n# current: one SELECT per job, in a loop\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\n**Fix** — batch the lookup, then split into `executemany` inserts/updates:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 500):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 variable limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 500]\n        placeholders = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        existing.update(cur.execute(\n            f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({placeholders})\",\n            chunk).fetchall() and {\n                r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in cur.execute(\n                    f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({placeholders})\", chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        if job.key not in existing:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif existing[job.key] != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    if new:\n        cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (...)\",\n                         [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    if changed:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\",\n                         [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                         [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\n(Simplify the chunking above — the point is: one `SELECT ... IN (...)` instead of N, and `executemany` instead of a per-row `execute` loop.)\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job (`filters.py:11-27`)\n\nThis is the most impactful \"unnecessary recomputation\" bug. `match()` is called once per job by `filter_jobs`, and it calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` **inside** that per-job call — so every include/exclude keyword regex gets recompiled from scratch for every single job in the batch.\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...)]\n    #                                              ^ match() recompiles regex every call\n```\n\n**Fix** — compile once, pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, locations=None, cutoff=None):\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\nWith N jobs and K keywords, this drops regex compilation from O(N·K) to O(K).\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `Job.to_row()` deep-copies `raw` just to discard it (`models.py:71-75`)\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)      # dataclasses.asdict recursively deep-copies every field,\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)    # including `raw` (a full parsed JSON job payload) — then drops it\n    ...\n```\n\n`dataclasses.asdict` recursively deep-copies nested structures. Since `raw` is a full parsed API response (e.g. the entire Greenhouse/Ashby job dict) and gets popped immediately, that recursive copy is pure waste on every insert/update.\n\n**Fix** — build the row dict directly instead of going through `asdict`:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    return {\n        \"key\": self.key, \"source\": self.source, \"company\": self.company,\n        \"external_id\": self.external_id, \"title\": self.title, \"url\": self.url,\n        \"location\": self.location, \"department\": self.department,\n        \"employment_type\": self.employment_type, \"posted_at\": self.posted_at,\n        \"salary_range\": self.salary_range, \"content_hash\": self.content_hash,\n    }\n```\n\nBonus: this also fixes a smaller double-hash issue — in `Store.diff()`, `job.content_hash` (a `@property` that runs SHA-256 over a joined string) currently gets computed once for the comparison and again inside `to_row()` for changed jobs. Once you hand-roll `to_row()`, it's easy to compute `content_hash` once and reuse it in both places (or memoize it since `Job` is otherwise immutable per-fetch).\n\n## What's already fine (no action needed)\n\n- `fetch_all` shares a single `httpx.AsyncClient` across all sources via a semaphore — no connection-per-request leak, good concurrency control already in place.\n- Pagination loops (`fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, etc.) all have `max_pages` safety caps and `seen: set[str]` dedup with O(1) membership checks — no unbounded growth.\n- `Store` connections are consistently used via context managers (`with Store(...) as store:`), so no dangling SQLite handles.\n- This is a short-lived batch CLI (not a long-running server), so classic \"memory leak\" concerns (unbounded caches, event listener accumulation) don't really apply here — nothing retains state across runs except the SQLite file itself.\n\n**Priority**: fix #2 (regex recompilation) first — it's the cheapest fix and scales worst (O(N·K)); then #1 (batch the store diff) since it's the main source of real I/O round-trips at scale; #3 is a smaller win but easy to fold into the #1 change.\n",
